Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Trim the @green beans{80%g} and chop into thirds. Halve the @plum{2}, remove the stones and chop the flesh into 1cm pieces. Zest and halve the @lemon{1/2}.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} over medium high heat. When hot, add the shallot and green beans. Stir and cook until beginning to soften, ~{3-4%minutes}. Stir in the @bulgur wheat{100%g} and @water{200%ml}.

Bring to the boil, stir in the @chicken stock powder{1/2} and half the lemon zest. Pop a lid on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve. This is your tabbouleh.

Meanwhile, heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium-high heat. When hot, add the plums and cook until browned and soft, stirring occasionally ~{3-4%minutes}. Transfer to a #small bowl{} and squeeze in the @honey{15%g}. Stir well and keep to one side.

Add a splash of @oil{} (if necessary) to the now empty frying pan and heat over medium-high heat. When hot, add the @pomegranate pork steak{2} and brown for ~{2%minutes} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Lower the heat and cook for another ~{2-3%minutes} on each side.

> IMPORTANT: The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the pork cooks, roughly chop the @dill{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Add half of the dill to the plum salsa and mix well. Fluff up the bulgur wheat with a #fork{} and stir through the remaining dill. Season to taste with @salt{}, @ground black pepper{}, the remaining lemon zest and some lemon juice.

Share the tabbouleh between your plates, lay the pork steak on top and finish with the plum salsa.